1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
This ivy-covered tree
is slowly ending
its very interesting life.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:10,000
If we move the ivy aside,
we can find a small sign.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,000
It says this is
a pedunculate oak

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:18,000
called
"The End and the Beginning".

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:23,000
The name comes from
a colorful art installation

6
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:28,000
made in 2012
by artist Łukasz Berg.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Back then, the tree
no longer looked

8
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,000
like the beautiful
nature monument
it once was.

9
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Its meaning
also changed.

10
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:48,000
As art, it showed
reconciliation,

11
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:57,000
brotherhood,
and inclusiveness.

12
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:04,000
But how did this oak
appear in the village center?

13
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
It was planted
in the dark 1930s,

14
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:13,000
when this land
was ruled
by the Third Reich.

15
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:19,000
It honored victims
of World War I,

16
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,000
but was also linked
to the Nazi idea
"Blood and Soil".

17
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Planting oaks
was meant
as a symbol.

18
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
It showed they wanted
to connect to

19
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,000
the Holy Roman Empire
from the early Middle Ages.

20
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
They believed
their empire would last

21
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
a thousand years,
like long-living oaks.

22
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:40,000
But it happened
differently.

23
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:47,000
The Third Reich fell
before the oak grew up.

24
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Even powerful ideas
can fade faster
than a simple tree.